            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Reyes\u2019s story is woven from the immigrant threads of the Bay Area. Born in Daly City to a Filipino mother who worked as a housekeeper and a Mexican father who spent his life as a union carpenter, Marco was raised on the principles of hard work and quiet dignity. His parents, who identified simply as \"American\" on forms but cherished their respective cultures at home, are why he marks his ethnicity as \"Other\"\u2014it feels more honest than choosing one over the other.\n\nHe was the first in his family to attend college, commuting from home to San Francisco State University. His Bachelor's in Business Administration wasn't a passion, but a practical tool he believed would build a more stable life than his parents had. He began his career in the late 90s as a project coordinator at a burgeoning biotech firm. While his peers chased the fleeting glory of the dot-com boom, Marco focused on methodical execution. This pragmatism saved his job during the bust of the early 2000s, a key turning point that cemented his reputation for reliability over flash. Over two decades, he steadily climbed the ladder, his promotions earned through diligence, not disruption.\n\nToday, Marco is the Director of Program Management at a biotech consulting firm in SoMa. He lives in the Inner Richmond with his wife, Elena, a public-school teacher. Their daughter, Sofia, is a sophomore at UC San Diego, and her departure has left their home feeling both larger and quieter. His daily routine is a testament to his grounded nature: a walk to the corner bakery for coffee, then the 5.1-mile ride on the N Judah, where he reads novels on his Kindle, a small act of analog rebellion in a digital world.\n\nMarco\u2019s connection to San Francisco is deep and unpretentious. He loves the city for its fog-draped avenues and the cacophony of languages on Clement Street, not for its disruptive startups. With his career stable and daughter thriving, his aspirations have shifted inward. He dreams of traveling through Southeast Asia and Oaxaca with Elena, to connect with the parts of his heritage he only knows through his parents\u2019 stories. More importantly, he has begun mentoring first-generation college students entering the tech and science fields, ensuring the ladder he so carefully climbed remains steady for the next person in line."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers standing in the doorway of their Daly City kitchen, maybe ten years old, watching his parents after a long day. The scent of sawdust still clung to his father\u2019s clothes, his quiet hands resting on the table. His mother moved with a practiced weariness, wiping down the counters. No grand speeches were ever made, but in that shared silence, he understood that hard work was their love language. It was the foundation they were building for him, one splinter and one scrubbed floor at a time, and it instilled in him a profound respect for quiet diligence.\n\n2.\nThe dot-com bust in 2001 was a landscape of panic. Marco watched brilliant, loud colleagues at his biotech firm, who\u2019d boasted about stock options, quietly pack their desk toys into cardboard boxes. He awaited his turn, certain his methodical, unglamorous work made him disposable. Instead, his manager stopped by his cubicle, simply clapping him on the shoulder. \"Your projects are on track, Marco. We need that.\" In that brief moment of relief, his entire career philosophy was cemented: reliability would always outlast the hype. It was a lesson he never forgot.\n\n3.\nHe can still feel the specific weight of Sofia\u2019s small bicycle as he held the seat, jogging alongside her in Golden Gate Park. She was six, her face a mask of determined terror. The moment he let go, she wobbled, then shouted with pure, unbridled joy as she pedaled away from him under her own power. A swell of pride hit him, immediately followed by the first, sharp pang of a future letting-go. It was the first time he truly understood his job as a father wasn\u2019t to hold on, but to prepare her to ride away.\n\n4.\nEarly in their marriage, he and Elena walked down Clement Street on a foggy Saturday night. The mist softened the streetlights into halos, and the air was a thick mix of languages and the scent of roasted duck from the delis. They bought pork buns from a tiny shop, their warmth seeping through the paper bag. He felt a deep, unshakeable sense of belonging. This wasn\u2019t the San Francisco of startups or cable cars; this was his city, a place built by people like his parents, and he was finally home.\n\n5.\nLast year, he met his first mentee for coffee. She was a first-generation student from SF State, her eyes wide with the same mix of ambition and anxiety he remembered in himself. She confessed her fear that choosing a stable biotech job was \"playing it too safe.\" Looking at her, Marco realized his meticulously built, practical career wasn't just a personal achievement; it was now a map he could share. He felt a new sense of purpose settle over him, realizing the ladder he\u2019d climbed was now sturdy enough for two."
